{
  "doc_id": "9454",
  "text": ". Production of NDs is a challenge as it requires extreme pressure and temperature conditions. Several methods have been proposed, including detonation [CITATION_1] , high-pressure-high-temperature (HPHT) growth [CITATION_2] , ultrasound cavitation [CITATION_3] , chemical vapor deposition [CITATION_4] and laser-assisted techniques [14] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Among the methods relying on laser irradiation, confined-pulsed-laser-ablation (CPLA) has been proposed as a potentially scalable and cost effective process for the production of NDs. In this approach, laser nanosecond pulses were applied to graphite confined between solid, transparent substrates that helped create favorable conditions for the formation of NDs [CITATION_7] . While potentially useful for a number of applications, including laser writing of patterned diamond films, harvesting of the NDs, e.g. for their use as nanoprobes in bioimaging applications, remains a problem.",
